subSubSection.paragraph:
Eggs:
Spherical, ornamented and laid freely (
Fig. 4A
), with the chorion surface of the 

hufelandi

type
(reticulated; 
Fig. 4B
). The reticulum well defined, with a limited mesh between egg processes. The mesh size almost uniform (1.0–1.8 µm in diameter), but the mesh forming peribasal rings around processes slightly larger than the interbasal mesh. Process trunks mostly sigmoidal, sometimes concave, wide at the base and very narrow just below the disc, occasionally bifurcated, and terminated with a concave disc (
Fig. 4C
). Disc edges indented, with well-developed teeth (
Fig. 4D
).

M. personatus Biserov, 1990
, reported from the type locality in Russia , by: the absence of granulation on legs I–III, the apparent absence of eyes, the presence of teeth on concave terminal discs of the egg processes (terminal discs flat and smooth in
M. personatus
), longer egg processes (11.8–20.0 µm in the new species vs. 7.0–10.5 µm in
M. personatus
), and a smaller diameter of terminal disc on egg processes (6.0–6.6 µm in the new species vs. 7.0– 9.0 µm in
M. personatus
).

M. sandrae Bertolani & Rebecchi, 1993
, reported from the type locality in Germany , by: the absence of granulation on legs I–III, the absence of teeth on lunules IV, the apparent absence of eyes, the presence of teeth on terminal discs of egg processes (terminal discs jagged, ragged or almost smooth, but never dentate in
M. sandrae
), a lower process base/height ratio (65–69% in the new species vs. 109–111% in
M. sandrae
), and higher egg processes (11.8–20.0 µm in the new species vs. 4.3–7.6 µm in
M. sandrae
).

M. serratus Bertolani et al. , 1996
, recorded from the type locality in Italy , by: the absence of teeth on lunules IV, the apparent absence of eyes, a higher pt of buccal tube width (
11.6–15.1 in
the new species
vs. 7.5–9.9
in
M. serratus
), a lower number of processes on the egg circumference ( ca. 20 in the new species vs. ca. 29 in
M. serratus
), higher egg processes (11.8–20.0 µm in new species vs. 5.5–8.0 µm in
M. serratus
), wider egg processes (8.2–8.6 µm in the new species vs. ca. 6.5 µm in
M. serratus
), and larger diameter of terminal discs of egg processes (6.0–6.6 µm in the new species vs. ca. 2.5 µm in
M. serratus
).

M. sottilei
Pilato et al. , 2012
, reported from the type locality in Belarus , by: the absence of granulation on legs I–III, the absence of teeth on lunules IV, the apparent absence of eyes, a higher pt of stylet supports (
77.0– 80.2
in the new species
vs. 75.3–76.6
in
M. sottilei
), a lower number of processes on the egg circumference ( ca. 20 in the new species vs. ca. 29 in
M. sottilei
), a lower process base/height ratio (65–69% in the new species vs. 84–89% in
M. sandrae
), higher egg processes (11.8–20.0 µm in the new species vs. 5.4–6.2 µm in
M. sottilei
), wider bases of egg processes (8.2–8.6 µm in the new species vs. 4.8–5.2 µm in
M. sottilei
), and a larger diameter of terminal discs of egg processes (6.0–6.6 µm in the new species vs. 3.6–4.4 µm in
M. sottilei
).

M. terminalis Bertolani & Rebecchi, 1993
, recorded from several localities in Italy , by: the absence of granulation on legs I–III, absence of teeth on lunules IV, the apparent absence of eyes, the presence of teeth on terminal discs of egg processes (terminal discs jagged in
M. terminalis
), a lower number of processes on the egg circumference ( ca. 20 in the new species vs. ca. 26 in
M. terminalis
), a lower process base/height ratio (65–69% in the new species vs. 111–123% in
M. terminalis
), longer egg processes (11.8–20.0 µm in the new species vs. 4.6–6.0 µm in
M. terminalis
), wider egg processes (8.2–8.6 µm in the new species vs. 5.1–7.4 µm in
M. terminalis
), and a larger diameter of terminal discs of egg processes (6.0–6.6 µm in the new species vs. 3.8–4.8 µm in
M. terminalis
).

M. vladimiri
Bertolani et al. , 2011
, reported from the type locality in Italy , by: the absence of granulation on legs I–III, the absence of teeth on lunules IV, the apparent absence of eyes, the presence of teeth on terminal discs of egg processes (terminal discs jagged in
M. vladimiri
), a lower process base/height ratio (65–69% in the new species vs. 78–91% in
M. vladimiri
), higher egg processes (11.8–20.0 µm in the new species vs. 6.5–8.0 µm in
M. vladimiri
), wider bases of egg processes (8.2–8.6 µm in the new species vs. 5.1–7.3 µm in
M. vladimiri
), and a larger diameter of terminal discs of egg processes (6.0–6.6 µm in the new species vs. 3.8–4.8 µm in
M. vladimiri
).
